The picture requires no explanation. It is Luther, the young monk of four-and-twenty, in the Library of the Convent of Erfurt. He is at his desk, leaning almost wildly forward, one knee on the seat—its foot has dropped the rude and worn sandal—the other foot on the floor, as it were pressing him forward. He is gazing into the open pages of a huge Vulgate —we see it is the early chapters of the Romans. A bit of broken chain indicates that the Bible was once chained—to be read, but not possessed-it is now free, and his own. His right hand is eagerly, pas- sionately drawing the volume close to him.
